dvocates, from bureaucrats to grassroots activists, adapted to this new political context. In Wong's view, the politics of democratic transition in Taiwan and South Korea has served as an effective antidote to the presumed economic imperatives of social welfare retrenchment during the process of globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocracyzKorea (South). 0aDemocracyzTaiwan. 0aPublic welfarezKorea (South). 0aPublic welfarezTaiwan. 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171148040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501711480423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501711480/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles